  "prompt": "Luis Von Ahn: What is the current business model of Duolingo?",
  "response": "Luis Von Ahn, the co-founder and CEO of Duolingo, has guided the company to adopt a freemium business model. Here's a breakdown of how it works:\n\n1. **Free Access**: The core of Duolingo's offerings is available for free. Users can access a wide range of language courses without any cost, supported by advertisements.\n\n2. **Duolingo Plus**: This is the premium subscription service, which offers an ad-free experience, offline access to lessons, and additional features like unlimited hearts (allowing more mistakes without interrupting the lesson flow) and monthly streak repairs. The subscription model generates significant revenue for the company.\n\n3. **Duolingo English Test**: Another revenue stream is the Duolingo English Test, a certified English proficiency test accepted by many universities and institutions worldwide. It's more affordable and quicker than traditional tests like TOEFL or IELTS, attracting a large user base.\n\n4. **In-App Purchases**: Users can make one-time purchases for features like streak freezes, which help maintain their learning streaks if they miss a day.\n\n5. **Advertising**: As mentioned, ads are shown to users who use the free version of the app. This is another source of revenue.\n\n6. **Duolingo for Schools**: This is a free tool that allows teachers to track their students' progress, aligning with educational institutions and potentially fostering long-term user engagement and brand loyalty.\n\nVon Ahn's strategy has been to make language learning accessible to as many people as possible while monetizing through premium features and additional services. This approach has proven successful, as evidenced by Duolingo's growth and its status as a leading language learning platform.",
